CBOW Workflow

Input Text
     ↓
Tokenization
     ↓
Create Context–Target Pairs
     ↓
Encode Words as Indices
     ↓
One-Hot Encoding
     ↓
CBOW Model
     ↓
Average Context Vectors
     ↓
Predict Target Word
     ↓
Calculate Loss/Error
     ↓
Backpropagation
     ↓
Update Word Vectors
     ↓
Repeat for Epochs
     ↓
Trained Word Vectors


===========

Step 1: Input Text

The model receives text.

Example:

The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog
Step 2: Tokenization

Split the sentence into individual words (tokens).

["The", "quick", "brown", "fox", "jumps", "over", "the", "lazy", "dog"]

Each word is called a token.

Step 3: Create Context–Target Pairs

Suppose window size = 2.

Sentence:

The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog
Pair 1

Context:

quick, brown, jumps, over

Target:

fox
Pair 2

Context:

The, brown

Target:

quick

Many such pairs are created from the sentence.

Step 4: Encode Words as Indices

Assign an integer ID to every word.

| Word  | Index |
| ----- | ----: |
| The   |     0 |
| quick |     1 |
| brown |     2 |
| fox   |     3 |
| jumps |     4 |
| over  |     5 |
| lazy  |     6 |
| dog   |     7 |

Now the sentence becomes:

0 1 2 3 4 5 0 6 7

=============

Step 5: One-Hot Encoding

Convert each index into a one-hot vector.

Example:

| Word  | One-Hot Vector    |
| ----- | ----------------- |
| The   | [1 0 0 0 0 0 0 0] |
| quick | [0 1 0 0 0 0 0 0] |
| brown | [0 0 1 0 0 0 0 0] |


These vectors contain mostly zeros and a single one.

==============

Step 6: CBOW Model

The model takes the context words as input.

Example:

Input:
quick
brown
jumps
over

Target:

fox

The CBOW neural network tries to predict fox.

===============

Step 7: Average Context Vectors

Each context word has an embedding vector.

Suppose:

quick = [0.2, 0.4, 0.6]
brown = [0.3, 0.5, 0.4]
jumps = [0.7, 0.2, 0.5]
over  = [0.4, 0.6, 0.8]

The CBOW model averages them.

Average:

[(0.2+0.3+0.7+0.4)/4,
 (0.4+0.5+0.2+0.6)/4,
 (0.6+0.4+0.5+0.8)/4]

=
[0.40, 0.425, 0.575]

This average vector represents the context.

=============

The values in a word embedding, such as 0.2, 0.4, and 0.6, are not manually calculated. 
They are initially assigned random values. During Word2Vec training, the neural network predicts target words, 
computes the prediction error, and updates these values using backpropagation and gradient descent.
After many training iterations, the vectors become meaningful representations of the words.

